They believed that no government or custom should prohibit the exercise of personal freedom. Early liberal feminists opposed the assumption that only white men deserved to be full citizens. Feminists such as Mary Wollstonecraft, Judith Sargent Murray, and Frances Wright advocated the full participation of women in political life [2]. In 1920, after almost 50 years of vigorous activity, women finally received the right to vote, as well as the right to hold public office in the United States, in 1928 - in Great Britain. Liberal feminism does not have a specific set of philosophies, which makes their beliefs rather abstract.